  </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: More bug stuff</span><hr size=1> My problems with Microsoft are that they are seeking to rule the world - and not in a good way.  I have no problem with someone making a good product and making a boatload of money - that's the American way, and I applaud for anyone who does it.  However, when that boatload of money comes from shamming the public with shoddy products that they have no choice but to buy, then there's a problem.<br>
<br>
Office XP, and the forthcoming Windows XP have new installer technology in it, which requires a hash key in order to run.  This hash key is generated when you install the product for the first time and can not be re-generated without contacting microsoft.  However, it must be re-generated if you change hardware configurations because it ties your hardware configuration to the hash key.<br>
<br>
Now, let's say I have a hard drive crash on a Friday night (I do work nights and weekends btw).  I break out my CD's to recover and I can't install a product that *I paid for* because I can't get through to tech support for 3-4 days.<br>
<br>
The biggest thing I hate is that Microsoft tries to be everything to everyone and fails.  Every one of their programs wants to have a high degree of control over your system, but they don't even work well with other Microsoft programs in some cases.<br>
<br>
I program a lot.  I use Visual Studio to work in C++.  Version 5 of Visual Studio required that you have IE 3.0 on your system.  If you had a later version, it OVERWROTE it with 3.0 (without asking).  Then I installed another program, which required version 4.0 of IE and installed it over 3.0 (again without asking).  Meaning I couldn't use Visual Studio any more without reinstalling it, which then broke my other program.  It was a vicious cycle.<br>
<br>
Every version of Office has bugs - some bugs in Excel have caused me to lose work more than once before I figured a way around.  Yet these bugs are never fixed.  New versions of Office come out (for a hefty upgrade fee) almost every year, yet there are bugs that I've been fighting since Excel version 2.0.<br>
<br>
Every version of Windows has more security holes than the last, but rather than fixing it, Microsoft doles out another version of Windows with a few new bells/whistles.  All the while hackers are merrily going about their business exploiting those security holes and trashing people's home systems and hacking web servers.<br>
<br>
As someone in this thread said earlier, WinME is a piece of crap.  But just try to buy a new computer that doesn't have it pre-installed.  I bought a laptop last fall and shopped around extensively.  It was *physically impossible* to buy a Windows laptop that did not have ME installed.<br>
<br>
A few years ago, every Microsoft product came with an extensive manual (usually hundreds of pages), and a toll-free number to call for support, which connected you with someone who knew how to use the product and was quite helpful.  Also, the help files were detailed and useful.<br>
<br>
Today, new Microsoft software comes with a 20-page manual, virtually no help files (or worse, the help files for older versions of the product) and a 900 number you can call for beaucoup bucks to get to talk to support people who know less than you do about the program.<br>
<br>
Do I use Microsoft products?  Yes, unless there is a viable alternative.  In most cases there isn't a viable alternative though, because they've run the competition out of business through their tactics. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/biggrin.gif width=15 height=15 BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(8/2/01 6:09:58 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://lag999.homestead.com/files/rtfm.gif width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: More bug stuff</span><hr size=1> Khieran says:  <b><i>However, when that boatload of money comes from shamming the public with shoddy products that they have no choice but to buy, then there's a problem.</b></i><br>
